rdf:Description.rdfs:label: RBMS Relationship_designators Vocabulary
rdf:Description.dcterms:title: RBMS Relationship_designators Vocabulary
rdf:Description.skos:definition: The RBMS Relationship_designators Vocabulary is a controlled vocabulary maintained by the Rare Books and Manuscripts Section of the Association of College and Research Libraries.

rdf:Description.skos:scopeNote: Use for the writer of manuscript annotations on a printed item.
Use for the entity responsible for conceiving, and perhaps also implementing, an original graphic design or work of art. Prefer "illustrator" for book illustrators.
Use for the entity to whom a license for printing or publishing has been transferred.
Use with a name associated with or found in an item or collection, but which cannot be determined to be that of a “former owner” or other relator indicative of provenance.
Use to relate an author, artist, etc. to a work for which there is or once was substantial authority for designating that person as author, creator, etc.
Use for an entity who carries or delivers a communication, order, or other message.
Use for the entity responsible for writing a commendation or testimonial for a work, which appears on or within the publication itself.
Use for an entity who conceives and perhaps also executes an artist's book.
Use for the entity responsible for the entire graphic design of a book, including arrangement of type and illustration, choice of materials, and process used.
Use for the entity responsible for the design of a dust jacket.
rdf:Description.skos:historyNote: SN and UFs approved 20100116; change term request, 200907

rdf:Description.skos:scopeNote: Use for a censor, bowdlerizer, expurgator, etc., official or private.

Use for the entity responsible for bringing together material from various sources, which has been arranged, described, and cataloged as a collection. The collector is neither the creator of the material nor the entity to whom manuscripts in the collection may have been addressed.
Use for the entity responsible for applying color to drawings, prints, photographs, maps, etc.
Use for the entity responsible for producing a work or publication by selecting and putting together material from the works of various persons or bodies.
Use for the entity responsible for documenting, preserving, or treating printed or manuscript material, works of art, artifacts, or specimens.

Use for an entity responsible for contributing to a larger work, such as a monographic anthology, serial publication, or other compilation of individual works. Do not use for an entity whose sole function in relation to a work is editor, author, compiler, or translator.
Use for the entity that corrected a manuscript, such as the scriptorium official who corrected the work of a scribe. For printed matter, use proofreader.
Use for the writer or recipient of a letter or other communication.

Use for the entity responsible for the graphic design of a book cover, album cover, slipcase, box, container, etc. For the entity responsible for the graphic design of an entire book, use book designer; for book jackets, use bookjacket designer.
Use for the entity to whom a book, manuscript, etc., is dedicated (NOT the recipient of a gift).
Use for the author of a dedication, which may be a formal statement or in epistolary or verse form.
Use for the entity responsible for placing material in the physical custody of a library or repository without transferring the legal title.
Use for the entity who donates a book, manuscript, etc., to the present owner; donors to previous owners are designated as former owner or inscriber.
Use for the entity responsible for executing artistic or technical drawings.

Use for the entity responsible for preparing for publication a work not primarily his/her/its own, such as by elucidating text, adding introductory or other critical matter, or technically directing an editorial staff.
Use for the entity responsible for executing a facsimile.
Use for the painter of a fore-edge painting.
Use for an entity that previously owned an item. For an entity giving the item to the present owner, use "donor."
Use for the entity in whose memory or honor a book, manuscript, etc. is donated.
Use for the entity responsible for conceiving, and perhaps also implementing, a design or illustration, usually to accompany a written text.
Use for the entity responsible for compiling an index.
Use for the entity that signs a presentation statement.
Use for an entity that takes part in a dialogue, conversation, or discussion. Do not use for participants in interviews, debates, or disputations.
Use for the entity responsible for permitting the temporary use of an item.
Use for the original recipient of the right to print or publish.
Use for the signer of a license, imprimatur, etc.
Use for the entity responsible for preparing the stone or plate for lithographic printing, including a graphic artist creating a design directly on the surface from which printing will be done.
Use for the entity responsible for marbling paper, cloth, leather, etc.

rdf:Description.skos:note: Proposed by Laura O'Keefe, 8/03. Although modern specialist usage recognizes distinctions among the functions of "medium," "psychic," "channel," and "clairvoyant," these terms appear to be less distinct in earlier works. This accounts for the inclusion of UFs that are not strictly equivalent according to specialists in psychic phenomena.
rdf:Description.skos:scopeNote: Use for an entity who purports to communicate with spirits.
Use for the entity responsible for the design of mechanisms of three-dimensional paper structures found in movable and pop-up books, greeting cards, etc.

Use for the entity responsible for commissioning a work. For the entity assuming primary responsibility for the production of a work, that is, the entity under the auspices of which a work is printed, published, etc., use “Sponsor.”
Use for the entity responsible for taking photographs, whether they are used in their original form or as reproductions.
Use for a person who physically operates a printing press. For the entity responsible for the production of printed matter, use Printer.
Use for the entity responsible for the production of printed matter. For a person who physically operates a printing press, use Pressman.
Use for printer of illustrations from plates.
Use for the entity responsible for making a relief, intaglio, or planographic printing surface.
Use for corrector of printed matter. For manuscripts, use corrector.
Use for the entity to whom correspondence is addressed.
Use for the amanuensis and for the writer of manuscripts proper.
Use for the entity from whom correspondence is sent.
Use for the entity whose signature appears without a presentation or other statement indicative of provenance. When there is a presentation statement, use inscriber.

Use for the entity responsible for sponsoring or funding the production of a work, e.g., the entity "under the auspices of which" a work was written, printed, published, etc. For the entity responsible for commissioning a work, use Patron.

Use for the entity responsible for purchasing or pledging to purchase an item in advance of its publication.Use for a person who purchases or pledges to purchase an item in advance of its publication.

Use for the entity responsible for preparing a handwritten or typewritten copy from original material, including from dictated or orally recorded material. For makers of pen-facsimiles, use facsimilist.
Use for the entity responsible for rendering a text from one language into another, or from an older form of a language into the modern form.
Use for the entity responsible for designing the type face used in a particular item.

Use for the entity primarily responsible for choice and arrangement of type used in an item. If the typographer is also responsible for other aspects of the graphic design (e.g., book designer), added entries for both functions may be used as desired.
Use for an entity who verifies the truthfulness of a documented event or action.
Use for the entity responsible for creating a printing surface by cutting the image in relief on the plank side of a wood block.
Use for the entity responsible for creating, publishing, and/or distributing a zine.
